host_routes.description: optional; list of IPv4 DMVPN peer host ip-addresses to which traffic is forwarded

for_mgmt.description: determined during creation time and cannot be toggled. A management tunnel cannot be used by wxlan rule or by wlan

hello_interval.description: in seconds, used as heartbeat to detect if a tunnel is alive. AP will try another peer after missing N hellos specified by hello_retries.

hostname.description: optional, overwrite the hostname in SCCRQ control message, default is “” or null, %H and %M can be used, which will be replace with corresponding values. %H: name of the ap if provided (and will be stripped so it can be used for hostname) and fallbacks to MAC, %M: MAC (e.g. 5c5b350e0060)

ipsec.description: IPSec-related configurations; requires DMVPN be enabled

enabled.description: whether ipsec is enabled, requires DMVPN be enabled

is_static.description: whether it’s static/unmanaged (i.e. no control session). As the session configurations are not compatible, cannot be toggled.

mtu.description: 0 to enable PMTU, 552-1500 to start PMTU with a lower MTU

secret.description: secret, ‘’ if no auth is used

sessions.description: sessions to be established with the tunnel. Has to be >= 1 in order for this tunnel to be useful. For management tunnel, it can only have 1

remote_id.description: remote-id of the session, has to be unique in the same tunnel

use_ap_as_session_ids.description: whether to use AP (last 4 bytes of MAC currently) as session ids

use_udp.description: whether to use UDP instead of IP (proto=115, which is default of L2TPv3)

schema.description:
WxLAN Tag
* type:
** client: created manually (e.g. on wireless client table, when they spot a device of interest, they can create an wxlan tag for it
** resource: created automatically when we discover a network resource
** subnet: create automatically when a subnet is discovered

* match:
** wlan_id, ap_id: values are a list of Wlan / Device ids
** client_mac: values are a list of MAC addresses

* radius_group: this is a smart tag that matches RADIUS-Filter-ID, Airespace-ACL-Name (VendorID=14179, VendorType=6) / Aruba-User-Role (VendorID=14823, VendorType=1)
* radius_username: this matches the ATTR-User-Name(1)
* radius_class: thie matches the ATTR-Class(25)
* radius_attr: the values are [ “6=1”, “26=10.2.3.4” ], this support other RADIUS attributes where we know the type
* radius_vendor: the values are [ “14179.10=1”, “14178.16=1.2.3.4” ], this matches vendor attributes and will be dynamically evaluated

protocol.description: tcp / udp / icmp / gre / any / ":protocol_number", `protocol_number` is between 1-254

schema.description:
WLAN
*Note:* portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

acct_interim_interval.description: how frequently should interim accounting be reported, 60-65535. default is 0 (use one specified in Access-Accept request from RADIUS Server). Very frequent messages can affect the performance of the radius server, 600 and up is recommended when enabled

acct_servers.description: list of RADIUS accounting servers, optional, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

allow_ipv6_ndp.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows or disallows ipv6 Neighbor Discovery packets to go through

allow_mdns.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows mDNS / Bonjour packets to go through

app_limit.description: bandwidth limiting for apps (applies to up/down)

apps.description: map from app key to bandwidth in kbps. app key defined in Get Application List

wxtag_ids.description: map from wxtag_id of Hostname Wxlan Tags to bandwidth in kbps

arp_filter.description: whether to enable smart arp filter

auth_server_selection.description: When ordered, AP will prefer and go back to the first server if possible

auth_servers.description: list of RADIUS authentication servers, at least one is needed if `auth type`==`eap`, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

auth_servers_nas_id.description: optional, up to 48 bytes, will be dynamically generated if not provided. used only for authentication servers

band.description: which radio the wlan should apply to, both (default) / 24 / 5

band_steer.description: whether to enable band_steering, this works only when band==both

band_steer_force_band5.description: force dual-band capable client to connect to 5G

block_blacklist_clients.description: whether to block the clients in the blacklist (up to first 256 macs)

client_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting per-client is enabled

client_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting per-client is enabled

coa_servers.description: list of COA (change of authorization) servers, optional

disable_11ax.description: some old WLAN drivers may not be compatible

disable_ht_vht_rates.description: to disable ht or vht rates

dns_server_rewrite.description: for radius_group-based DNS server (rewrite DNS request depending on the Group RADIUS server returns)

radius_groups.description: map between radius_group and the desired DNS server (IPv4 only)

dynamic_psk.description:
for dynamic PSK where we get per-user PSK from Radius
dynamic_psk allows PSK to be selected at runtime depending on context (wlan/site/user/...) thus following configurations are assumed (currently)
- PSK will come from RADIUS server
- AP sends client MAC as username ans password (i.e. `enable_mac_auth` is assumed)
- AP sends BSSID:SSID as Caller-Station-ID
- `auth_servers` is required
- PSK will come from cloud WLC if source is cloud_psks
- default_psk will be used if cloud WLC is not available
- `multi_psk_only` and `psk` is ignored
- `pairwise` can only be wpa2-ccmp (for now, wpa3 support on the roadmap)

default_psk.description: default PSK to use if cloud WLC is not available, 8-63 characters

default_vlan_id.description: vlan_id to use when there’s no match from RADIUS

vlans.description: map between vlan_id (as string) to airespace interface names (comma-separated) or null for stndard mapping

enable_wireless_bridging.description:
whether to enable wireless bridging, which allows more broadcast packets to go through
(allows forwarding of DHCP response to client not associated with the AP)

hide_ssid.description: whether to hide SSID in beacon

hostname_ie.description: include hostname inside IE in AP beacons / probe responses

interface.description: where this WLAN will be connected to

isolation.description: whether to allow clients to talk to each other

legacy_overds.description: legacy devices requires the Over-DS (for Fast BSS Transition) bit set (while our chip doesn’t support it). Warning! Enabling this will cause problem for iOS devices.

limit_bcast.description: whether to limit broadcast packets going to wireless (i.e. only allow certain bcast packets to go through)

limit_probe_response.description: limit probe response base on some heuristic rules

mxtunnel.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, the definition of the Mist Tunnels (key is the name)

mxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`mxtunnel`, id of the Mist Tunnel

mxtunnel_name.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, name of the mxtunnel that in mxtunnels under Site Setting

no_static_dns.description: whether to only allow client to use DNS that we’ve learned from DHCP response

no_static_ip.description: whether to only allow client that we’ve learned from DHCP exchange to talk

portal_allowed_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring)

portal_api_secret.description: api secret (auto-generated) that can be used to sign guest authorization requests

portal_denied_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring), this takes precedence over portal_allowed_hostnames

portal_template_url.description: N.B portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

schedule.description: WLAN operating schedule, default is disabled

hours.description: time ranges, the key is mon / tue / wed / thu / fri / sat / sun, the value is time range in “HH:MM-HH:MM” (24-hour format), the minimum resolution is 30 minute

sle_excluded.description: whether to exclude this WLAN from SLE metrics

thumbnail.description: Url of portal background image thumbnail

use_eapol_v1.description: if `auth.type`==’eap’ or ‘psk’, should only be set for legacy client, such as pre-2004, 802.11b devices

vlan_pooling.description: vlan pooling allows AP to place client on different VLAN using a deterministic algorithm

wlan_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wlan_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`wxtunnel`, id of the WXLAN Tunnel

dns_server_rewrite.description: for radius_group-based DNS server (rewrite DNS request depending on the Group RADIUS server returns)

radius_groups.description: map between radius_group and the desired DNS server (IPv4 only)

dynamic_psk.description:
for dynamic PSK where we get per-user PSK from Radius
dynamic_psk allows PSK to be selected at runtime depending on context (wlan/site/user/...) thus following configurations are assumed (currently)
- PSK will come from RADIUS server
- AP sends client MAC as username ans password (i.e. `enable_mac_auth` is assumed)
- AP sends BSSID:SSID as Caller-Station-ID
- `auth_servers` is required
- PSK will come from cloud WLC if source is cloud_psks
- default_psk will be used if cloud WLC is not available
- `multi_psk_only` and `psk` is ignored
- `pairwise` can only be wpa2-ccmp (for now, wpa3 support on the roadmap)

default_psk.description: default PSK to use if cloud WLC is not available, 8-63 characters

default_vlan_id.description: vlan_id to use when there’s no match from RADIUS

vlans.description: map between vlan_id (as string) to airespace interface names (comma-separated) or null for stndard mapping

enable_wireless_bridging.description:
whether to enable wireless bridging, which allows more broadcast packets to go through
(allows forwarding of DHCP response to client not associated with the AP)

hide_ssid.description: whether to hide SSID in beacon

hostname_ie.description: include hostname inside IE in AP beacons / probe responses

interface.description: where this WLAN will be connected to

isolation.description: whether to allow clients to talk to each other

legacy_overds.description: legacy devices requires the Over-DS (for Fast BSS Transition) bit set (while our chip doesn’t support it). Warning! Enabling this will cause problem for iOS devices.

limit_bcast.description: whether to limit broadcast packets going to wireless (i.e. only allow certain bcast packets to go through)

limit_probe_response.description: limit probe response base on some heuristic rules

mxtunnel.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, the definition of the Mist Tunnels (key is the name)

mxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`mxtunnel`, id of the Mist Tunnel

mxtunnel_name.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, name of the mxtunnel that in mxtunnels under Site Setting

no_static_dns.description: whether to only allow client to use DNS that we’ve learned from DHCP response

no_static_ip.description: whether to only allow client that we’ve learned from DHCP exchange to talk

portal_allowed_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring)

portal_api_secret.description: api secret (auto-generated) that can be used to sign guest authorization requests

portal_denied_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring), this takes precedence over portal_allowed_hostnames

portal_template_url.description: N.B portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

schedule.description: WLAN operating schedule, default is disabled

hours.description: time ranges, the key is mon / tue / wed / thu / fri / sat / sun, the value is time range in “HH:MM-HH:MM” (24-hour format), the minimum resolution is 30 minute

sle_excluded.description: whether to exclude this WLAN from SLE metrics

thumbnail.description: Url of portal background image thumbnail

use_eapol_v1.description: if `auth.type`==’eap’ or ‘psk’, should only be set for legacy client, such as pre-2004, 802.11b devices

vlan_pooling.description: vlan pooling allows AP to place client on different VLAN using a deterministic algorithm

wlan_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wlan_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`wxtunnel`, id of the WXLAN Tunnel

schema.description:
WLAN
*Note:* portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

acct_interim_interval.description: how frequently should interim accounting be reported, 60-65535. default is 0 (use one specified in Access-Accept request from RADIUS Server). Very frequent messages can affect the performance of the radius server, 600 and up is recommended when enabled

acct_servers.description: list of RADIUS accounting servers, optional, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

allow_ipv6_ndp.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows or disallows ipv6 Neighbor Discovery packets to go through

allow_mdns.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows mDNS / Bonjour packets to go through

app_limit.description: bandwidth limiting for apps (applies to up/down)

apps.description: map from app key to bandwidth in kbps. app key defined in Get Application List

wxtag_ids.description: map from wxtag_id of Hostname Wxlan Tags to bandwidth in kbps

arp_filter.description: whether to enable smart arp filter

auth_server_selection.description: When ordered, AP will prefer and go back to the first server if possible

auth_servers.description: list of RADIUS authentication servers, at least one is needed if `auth type`==`eap`, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

auth_servers_nas_id.description: optional, up to 48 bytes, will be dynamically generated if not provided. used only for authentication servers

band.description: which radio the wlan should apply to, both (default) / 24 / 5

band_steer.description: whether to enable band_steering, this works only when band==both

band_steer_force_band5.description: force dual-band capable client to connect to 5G

block_blacklist_clients.description: whether to block the clients in the blacklist (up to first 256 macs)

client_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting per-client is enabled

client_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting per-client is enabled

coa_servers.description: list of COA (change of authorization) servers, optional

disable_11ax.description: some old WLAN drivers may not be compatible

disable_ht_vht_rates.description: to disable ht or vht rates

dns_server_rewrite.description: for radius_group-based DNS server (rewrite DNS request depending on the Group RADIUS server returns)

radius_groups.description: map between radius_group and the desired DNS server (IPv4 only)

dynamic_psk.description:
for dynamic PSK where we get per-user PSK from Radius
dynamic_psk allows PSK to be selected at runtime depending on context (wlan/site/user/...) thus following configurations are assumed (currently)
- PSK will come from RADIUS server
- AP sends client MAC as username ans password (i.e. `enable_mac_auth` is assumed)
- AP sends BSSID:SSID as Caller-Station-ID
- `auth_servers` is required
- PSK will come from cloud WLC if source is cloud_psks
- default_psk will be used if cloud WLC is not available
- `multi_psk_only` and `psk` is ignored
- `pairwise` can only be wpa2-ccmp (for now, wpa3 support on the roadmap)

default_psk.description: default PSK to use if cloud WLC is not available, 8-63 characters

default_vlan_id.description: vlan_id to use when there’s no match from RADIUS

vlans.description: map between vlan_id (as string) to airespace interface names (comma-separated) or null for stndard mapping

enable_wireless_bridging.description:
whether to enable wireless bridging, which allows more broadcast packets to go through
(allows forwarding of DHCP response to client not associated with the AP)

hide_ssid.description: whether to hide SSID in beacon

hostname_ie.description: include hostname inside IE in AP beacons / probe responses

interface.description: where this WLAN will be connected to

isolation.description: whether to allow clients to talk to each other

legacy_overds.description: legacy devices requires the Over-DS (for Fast BSS Transition) bit set (while our chip doesn’t support it). Warning! Enabling this will cause problem for iOS devices.

limit_bcast.description: whether to limit broadcast packets going to wireless (i.e. only allow certain bcast packets to go through)

limit_probe_response.description: limit probe response base on some heuristic rules

mxtunnel.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, the definition of the Mist Tunnels (key is the name)

mxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`mxtunnel`, id of the Mist Tunnel

mxtunnel_name.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, name of the mxtunnel that in mxtunnels under Site Setting

no_static_dns.description: whether to only allow client to use DNS that we’ve learned from DHCP response

no_static_ip.description: whether to only allow client that we’ve learned from DHCP exchange to talk

portal_allowed_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring)

portal_api_secret.description: api secret (auto-generated) that can be used to sign guest authorization requests

portal_denied_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring), this takes precedence over portal_allowed_hostnames

portal_template_url.description: N.B portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

schedule.description: WLAN operating schedule, default is disabled

hours.description: time ranges, the key is mon / tue / wed / thu / fri / sat / sun, the value is time range in “HH:MM-HH:MM” (24-hour format), the minimum resolution is 30 minute

sle_excluded.description: whether to exclude this WLAN from SLE metrics

thumbnail.description: Url of portal background image thumbnail

use_eapol_v1.description: if `auth.type`==’eap’ or ‘psk’, should only be set for legacy client, such as pre-2004, 802.11b devices

vlan_pooling.description: vlan pooling allows AP to place client on different VLAN using a deterministic algorithm

wlan_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wlan_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`wxtunnel`, id of the WXLAN Tunnel

schema.description:
Webhook
NOTE: 
 * when `secret` is provided, two HTTP headers will be added:
   * `X-Mist-Signature-v2`: HMAC_SHA256(secret, body)
   * `X-Mist-Signature`: HMAC_SHA1(secret, body)
 * If `headers` format is invalid, “X-Mist-Error”: “headers format invalid” will be sent.
 * If total bytes of `headers` exceed 1000, “X-Mist-Error”: “headers too big” will be sent.
 * If any header value is not `string`, “X-Mist-Error”: “header[%s] not a string” will be sent.

headers.description: custom headers : the headers name and value must be string, total bytes of headers name and value must be less than 1000

secret.description: optional, when type=http-post, if provided, additional signature HTTP headers will be added (see note below)

topics.description: N.B. For org webhooks, only device-events/alarms/audits/client-join/client-sessions topics are supported.

verify_cert.description: when url uses HTTPS, whether to verify the certificate

assets.description: list of ble assets currently in the zone and when they entered

p95.description: 95th percentile of all the wait time(s)

clients.description: list of clients currently in the zone and when they entered

sdkclients.description: list of sdkclients currently in the zone and when they entered

map_id.description: map_id of the sdk client (if known), or null

name.description: name of the sdk client (if provided)

network_connection.description: various network connection info for the SDK client (if known, else omitted), with RSSI in dBm, and signal level as

vbeacons.description: list of beacon_id’s of the sdk client is in and since when (if known)

x.description: x (in pixels) of user location on the map (if known)

y.description: y (in pixels) of user location on the map (if known)

zones.description: list of zone_id’s of the sdk client is in and since when (if known)

idle.description: percentage of Idle, Idle/(Idle + Busy) since last sampling

interrupt.description: percentage of Interrupt, (Irq + SoftIrq)/(Idle + Busy) since last sampling

system.description: percentage of System, System/(Idle + Busy) since last sampling

usage.description: percentage of load, Busy/(Idle + Busy) since last sampling

user.description: percentage of User, User/(Idle + Busy) since last sampling

active.description: The amount of memory, in kibibytes, that has been used more recently and is usually not reclaimed unless absolutely necessary.

available.description: An estimate of how much memory is available for starting new applications, without swapping.

buffers.description: The amount, in kibibytes, of temporary storage for raw disk blocks.

cached.description: The amount of physical RAM, in kibibytes, used as cache memory.

free.description: The amount of physical RAM, in kibibytes, left unused by the system.

inactive.description: The amount of memory, in kibibytes, that has been used less recently and is more eligible to be reclaimed for other purposes.

swap_cached.description: The amount of memory, in kibibytes, that has once been moved into swap, then back into the main memory, but still also remains in the swapfile.

swap_free.description: The total amount of swap free, in kibibytes.

swap_total.description: The total amount of swap available, in kibibytes.

total.description: Total amount of usable RAM, in kibibytes, which is physical RAM minus a number of reserved bits and the kernel binary code.

_ttl.description: TTL of the validity of the stat

accuracy.description: estimated clinet location accuracy, in meter

ap_id.description: AP ID the client is connected to

ap_mac.description: AP the client is connected to

dual_band.description: whether the client is dual-band capable (determined by whether we’ve seen probe requests from both bands)

family.description: device family, through fingerprinting. iPod / Nexus Galaxy / Windows Mobile or CE …

authorized_expiring_time.description: when the guest authorization will expire

hostname.description: hostname that we learned from sniffing DHCP

idle_time.description: how long, in seconds, has the client been idle (since the last RX packet)

manufacture.description: device manufacture, through fingerprinting or OUI

model.description: device model, may be available if we can identify them

num_locating_aps.description: number of APs used to locate this client

power_saving.description: if it’s currently in power-save mode

rx_bps.description: rate of receiving traffic from the clients, bits/seconds, last known

rx_bytes.description: amount of traffic received from client since client connects

rx_packets.description: amount of traffic received from client since client connects

ssid.description: SSID the client is connected to

tx_bps.description: rate of transmitting traffic to the clients, bits/seconds, last known

tx_bytes.description: amount of traffic sent to client since client connects

tx_packets.description: amount of traffic sent to client since client connects

type.description: client’s type, regular / vip / resource / blocked (if client object is created)

uptime.description: how long, in seconds, has the client been connected

username.description: username that we learned from 802.1X exchange or Per-user PSK or User Portal

vlan_id.description: vlan id, could be empty (from older AP)

wlan_id.description: WLAN ID the client is connected to

holding_time.description: optional; the holding time for NHRP ‘registration requests’ and ‘resolution replies’ sent from the Mist AP (in seconds); default 600

host_routes.description: optional; list of IPv4 DMVPN peer host ip-addresses to which traffic is forwarded

for_mgmt.description: determined during creation time and cannot be toggled. A management tunnel cannot be used by wxlan rule or by wlan

hello_interval.description: in seconds, used as heartbeat to detect if a tunnel is alive. AP will try another peer after missing N hellos specified by hello_retries.

hostname.description: optional, overwrite the hostname in SCCRQ control message, default is “” or null, %H and %M can be used, which will be replace with corresponding values. %H: name of the ap if provided (and will be stripped so it can be used for hostname) and fallbacks to MAC, %M: MAC (e.g. 5c5b350e0060)

ipsec.description: IPSec-related configurations; requires DMVPN be enabled

enabled.description: whether ipsec is enabled, requires DMVPN be enabled

is_static.description: whether it’s static/unmanaged (i.e. no control session). As the session configurations are not compatible, cannot be toggled.

mtu.description: 0 to enable PMTU, 552-1500 to start PMTU with a lower MTU

peers.description: list of remote peers’ IP or hostname

router_id.description: optional, overwrite the router-id in SCCRQ control message, default is “0” or null, can also be an IPv4 address

secret.description: secret, ‘’ if no auth is used

sessions.description: sessions to be established with the tunnel. Has to be >= 1 in order for this tunnel to be useful. For management tunnel, it can only have 1

ap_as_session_id.description: if `use_ap_as_session_ids`==`true`, only apmac is supported right now. This is the name WLAN should use for wxtunnel_remote_id

comment.description: optional, user-specified string for display purpose

pseudo_802.1ad_enabled.description: optional. Enables the pseudo 802.1ad QinQ mode where the AP device drops the outer vlan tag (QinQ). This mode is useful when tunneling Mist AP’s to some aggregation routers.

remote_id.description: remote-id of the session, has to be unique in the same tunnel

use_ap_as_session_ids.description: whether to use AP (last 4 bytes of MAC currently) as session ids

use_udp.description: whether to use UDP instead of IP (proto=115, which is default of L2TPv3)

schema.description:
WxLAN Tag
* type:
** client: created manually (e.g. on wireless client table, when they spot a device of interest, they can create an wxlan tag for it
** resource: created automatically when we discover a network resource
** subnet: create automatically when a subnet is discovered

* match:
** wlan_id, ap_id: values are a list of Wlan / Device ids
** client_mac: values are a list of MAC addresses

* radius_group: this is a smart tag that matches RADIUS-Filter-ID, Airespace-ACL-Name (VendorID=14179, VendorType=6) / Aruba-User-Role (VendorID=14823, VendorType=1)
* radius_username: this matches the ATTR-User-Name(1)
* radius_class: thie matches the ATTR-Class(25)
* radius_attr: the values are [ “6=1”, “26=10.2.3.4” ], this support other RADIUS attributes where we know the type
* radius_vendor: the values are [ “14179.10=1”, “14178.16=1.2.3.4” ], this matches vendor attributes and will be dynamically evaluated

protocol.description: tcp / udp / icmp / gre / any / ":protocol_number", `protocol_number` is between 1-254

schema.description:
WLAN
*Note:* portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

acct_interim_interval.description: how frequently should interim accounting be reported, 60-65535. default is 0 (use one specified in Access-Accept request from RADIUS Server). Very frequent messages can affect the performance of the radius server, 600 and up is recommended when enabled

acct_servers.description: list of RADIUS accounting servers, optional, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

allow_ipv6_ndp.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows or disallows ipv6 Neighbor Discovery packets to go through

allow_mdns.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows mDNS / Bonjour packets to go through

app_limit.description: bandwidth limiting for apps (applies to up/down)

apps.description: map from app key to bandwidth in kbps. app key defined in Get Application List

wxtag_ids.description: map from wxtag_id of Hostname Wxlan Tags to bandwidth in kbps

arp_filter.description: whether to enable smart arp filter

auth_server_selection.description: When ordered, AP will prefer and go back to the first server if possible

auth_servers.description: list of RADIUS authentication servers, at least one is needed if `auth type`==`eap`, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

auth_servers_nas_id.description: optional, up to 48 bytes, will be dynamically generated if not provided. used only for authentication servers

band.description: which radio the wlan should apply to, both (default) / 24 / 5

band_steer.description: whether to enable band_steering, this works only when band==both

band_steer_force_band5.description: force dual-band capable client to connect to 5G

block_blacklist_clients.description: whether to block the clients in the blacklist (up to first 256 macs)

client_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting per-client is enabled

client_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting per-client is enabled

coa_servers.description: list of COA (change of authorization) servers, optional

disable_11ax.description: some old WLAN drivers may not be compatible

disable_ht_vht_rates.description: to disable ht or vht rates

dns_server_rewrite.description: for radius_group-based DNS server (rewrite DNS request depending on the Group RADIUS server returns)

radius_groups.description: map between radius_group and the desired DNS server (IPv4 only)

dynamic_psk.description:
for dynamic PSK where we get per-user PSK from Radius
dynamic_psk allows PSK to be selected at runtime depending on context (wlan/site/user/...) thus following configurations are assumed (currently)
- PSK will come from RADIUS server
- AP sends client MAC as username ans password (i.e. `enable_mac_auth` is assumed)
- AP sends BSSID:SSID as Caller-Station-ID
- `auth_servers` is required
- PSK will come from cloud WLC if source is cloud_psks
- default_psk will be used if cloud WLC is not available
- `multi_psk_only` and `psk` is ignored
- `pairwise` can only be wpa2-ccmp (for now, wpa3 support on the roadmap)

default_psk.description: default PSK to use if cloud WLC is not available, 8-63 characters

default_vlan_id.description: vlan_id to use when there’s no match from RADIUS

vlans.description: map between vlan_id (as string) to airespace interface names (comma-separated) or null for stndard mapping

enable_wireless_bridging.description:
whether to enable wireless bridging, which allows more broadcast packets to go through
(allows forwarding of DHCP response to client not associated with the AP)

hide_ssid.description: whether to hide SSID in beacon

hostname_ie.description: include hostname inside IE in AP beacons / probe responses

interface.description: where this WLAN will be connected to

isolation.description: whether to allow clients to talk to each other

legacy_overds.description: legacy devices requires the Over-DS (for Fast BSS Transition) bit set (while our chip doesn’t support it). Warning! Enabling this will cause problem for iOS devices.

limit_bcast.description: whether to limit broadcast packets going to wireless (i.e. only allow certain bcast packets to go through)

limit_probe_response.description: limit probe response base on some heuristic rules

mxtunnel.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, the definition of the Mist Tunnels (key is the name)

mxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`mxtunnel`, id of the Mist Tunnel

mxtunnel_name.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, name of the mxtunnel that in mxtunnels under Site Setting

no_static_dns.description: whether to only allow client to use DNS that we’ve learned from DHCP response

no_static_ip.description: whether to only allow client that we’ve learned from DHCP exchange to talk

portal_allowed_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring)

portal_api_secret.description: api secret (auto-generated) that can be used to sign guest authorization requests

portal_denied_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring), this takes precedence over portal_allowed_hostnames

portal_template_url.description: N.B portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

schedule.description: WLAN operating schedule, default is disabled

hours.description: time ranges, the key is mon / tue / wed / thu / fri / sat / sun, the value is time range in “HH:MM-HH:MM” (24-hour format), the minimum resolution is 30 minute

sle_excluded.description: whether to exclude this WLAN from SLE metrics

thumbnail.description: Url of portal background image thumbnail

use_eapol_v1.description: if `auth.type`==’eap’ or ‘psk’, should only be set for legacy client, such as pre-2004, 802.11b devices

vlan_pooling.description: vlan pooling allows AP to place client on different VLAN using a deterministic algorithm

wlan_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wlan_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`wxtunnel`, id of the WXLAN Tunnel

schema.description:
WLAN
*Note:* portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

acct_interim_interval.description: how frequently should interim accounting be reported, 60-65535. default is 0 (use one specified in Access-Accept request from RADIUS Server). Very frequent messages can affect the performance of the radius server, 600 and up is recommended when enabled

acct_servers.description: list of RADIUS accounting servers, optional, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

allow_ipv6_ndp.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows or disallows ipv6 Neighbor Discovery packets to go through

allow_mdns.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows mDNS / Bonjour packets to go through

app_limit.description: bandwidth limiting for apps (applies to up/down)

apps.description: map from app key to bandwidth in kbps. app key defined in Get Application List

wxtag_ids.description: map from wxtag_id of Hostname Wxlan Tags to bandwidth in kbps

arp_filter.description: whether to enable smart arp filter

auth_server_selection.description: When ordered, AP will prefer and go back to the first server if possible

auth_servers.description: list of RADIUS authentication servers, at least one is needed if `auth type`==`eap`, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

auth_servers_nas_id.description: optional, up to 48 bytes, will be dynamically generated if not provided. used only for authentication servers

band.description: which radio the wlan should apply to, both (default) / 24 / 5

band_steer.description: whether to enable band_steering, this works only when band==both

band_steer_force_band5.description: force dual-band capable client to connect to 5G

block_blacklist_clients.description: whether to block the clients in the blacklist (up to first 256 macs)

client_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting per-client is enabled

client_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting per-client is enabled

coa_servers.description: list of COA (change of authorization) servers, optional

disable_11ax.description: some old WLAN drivers may not be compatible

disable_ht_vht_rates.description: to disable ht or vht rates

dns_server_rewrite.description: for radius_group-based DNS server (rewrite DNS request depending on the Group RADIUS server returns)

radius_groups.description: map between radius_group and the desired DNS server (IPv4 only)

dynamic_psk.description:
for dynamic PSK where we get per-user PSK from Radius
dynamic_psk allows PSK to be selected at runtime depending on context (wlan/site/user/...) thus following configurations are assumed (currently)
- PSK will come from RADIUS server
- AP sends client MAC as username ans password (i.e. `enable_mac_auth` is assumed)
- AP sends BSSID:SSID as Caller-Station-ID
- `auth_servers` is required
- PSK will come from cloud WLC if source is cloud_psks
- default_psk will be used if cloud WLC is not available
- `multi_psk_only` and `psk` is ignored
- `pairwise` can only be wpa2-ccmp (for now, wpa3 support on the roadmap)

default_psk.description: default PSK to use if cloud WLC is not available, 8-63 characters

default_vlan_id.description: vlan_id to use when there’s no match from RADIUS

vlans.description: map between vlan_id (as string) to airespace interface names (comma-separated) or null for stndard mapping

enable_wireless_bridging.description:
whether to enable wireless bridging, which allows more broadcast packets to go through
(allows forwarding of DHCP response to client not associated with the AP)

hide_ssid.description: whether to hide SSID in beacon

hostname_ie.description: include hostname inside IE in AP beacons / probe responses

interface.description: where this WLAN will be connected to

isolation.description: whether to allow clients to talk to each other

legacy_overds.description: legacy devices requires the Over-DS (for Fast BSS Transition) bit set (while our chip doesn’t support it). Warning! Enabling this will cause problem for iOS devices.

limit_bcast.description: whether to limit broadcast packets going to wireless (i.e. only allow certain bcast packets to go through)

limit_probe_response.description: limit probe response base on some heuristic rules

mxtunnel.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, the definition of the Mist Tunnels (key is the name)

mxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`mxtunnel`, id of the Mist Tunnel

mxtunnel_name.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, name of the mxtunnel that in mxtunnels under Site Setting

no_static_dns.description: whether to only allow client to use DNS that we’ve learned from DHCP response

no_static_ip.description: whether to only allow client that we’ve learned from DHCP exchange to talk

portal_allowed_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring)

portal_api_secret.description: api secret (auto-generated) that can be used to sign guest authorization requests

portal_denied_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring), this takes precedence over portal_allowed_hostnames

portal_template_url.description: N.B portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

schedule.description: WLAN operating schedule, default is disabled

hours.description: time ranges, the key is mon / tue / wed / thu / fri / sat / sun, the value is time range in “HH:MM-HH:MM” (24-hour format), the minimum resolution is 30 minute

sle_excluded.description: whether to exclude this WLAN from SLE metrics

thumbnail.description: Url of portal background image thumbnail

use_eapol_v1.description: if `auth.type`==’eap’ or ‘psk’, should only be set for legacy client, such as pre-2004, 802.11b devices

vlan_pooling.description: vlan pooling allows AP to place client on different VLAN using a deterministic algorithm

wlan_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wlan_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`wxtunnel`, id of the WXLAN Tunnel

schema.description:
WLAN
*Note:* portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

acct_interim_interval.description: how frequently should interim accounting be reported, 60-65535. default is 0 (use one specified in Access-Accept request from RADIUS Server). Very frequent messages can affect the performance of the radius server, 600 and up is recommended when enabled

acct_servers.description: list of RADIUS accounting servers, optional, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

allow_ipv6_ndp.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows or disallows ipv6 Neighbor Discovery packets to go through

allow_mdns.description: only applicable when limit_bcast==true, which allows mDNS / Bonjour packets to go through

app_limit.description: bandwidth limiting for apps (applies to up/down)

apps.description: map from app key to bandwidth in kbps. app key defined in Get Application List

wxtag_ids.description: map from wxtag_id of Hostname Wxlan Tags to bandwidth in kbps

arp_filter.description: whether to enable smart arp filter

auth_server_selection.description: When ordered, AP will prefer and go back to the first server if possible

auth_servers.description: list of RADIUS authentication servers, at least one is needed if `auth type`==`eap`, order matters where the first one is treated as primary

auth_servers_nas_id.description: optional, up to 48 bytes, will be dynamically generated if not provided. used only for authentication servers

band.description: which radio the wlan should apply to, both (default) / 24 / 5

band_steer.description: whether to enable band_steering, this works only when band==both

band_steer_force_band5.description: force dual-band capable client to connect to 5G

block_blacklist_clients.description: whether to block the clients in the blacklist (up to first 256 macs)

client_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting per-client is enabled

client_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting per-client is enabled

coa_servers.description: list of COA (change of authorization) servers, optional

disable_11ax.description: some old WLAN drivers may not be compatible

disable_ht_vht_rates.description: to disable ht or vht rates

dns_server_rewrite.description: for radius_group-based DNS server (rewrite DNS request depending on the Group RADIUS server returns)

radius_groups.description: map between radius_group and the desired DNS server (IPv4 only)

dynamic_psk.description:
for dynamic PSK where we get per-user PSK from Radius
dynamic_psk allows PSK to be selected at runtime depending on context (wlan/site/user/...) thus following configurations are assumed (currently)
- PSK will come from RADIUS server
- AP sends client MAC as username ans password (i.e. `enable_mac_auth` is assumed)
- AP sends BSSID:SSID as Caller-Station-ID
- `auth_servers` is required
- PSK will come from cloud WLC if source is cloud_psks
- default_psk will be used if cloud WLC is not available
- `multi_psk_only` and `psk` is ignored
- `pairwise` can only be wpa2-ccmp (for now, wpa3 support on the roadmap)

default_psk.description: default PSK to use if cloud WLC is not available, 8-63 characters

default_vlan_id.description: vlan_id to use when there’s no match from RADIUS

vlans.description: map between vlan_id (as string) to airespace interface names (comma-separated) or null for stndard mapping

enable_wireless_bridging.description:
whether to enable wireless bridging, which allows more broadcast packets to go through
(allows forwarding of DHCP response to client not associated with the AP)

hide_ssid.description: whether to hide SSID in beacon

hostname_ie.description: include hostname inside IE in AP beacons / probe responses

interface.description: where this WLAN will be connected to

isolation.description: whether to allow clients to talk to each other

legacy_overds.description: legacy devices requires the Over-DS (for Fast BSS Transition) bit set (while our chip doesn’t support it). Warning! Enabling this will cause problem for iOS devices.

limit_bcast.description: whether to limit broadcast packets going to wireless (i.e. only allow certain bcast packets to go through)

limit_probe_response.description: limit probe response base on some heuristic rules

mxtunnel.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, the definition of the Mist Tunnels (key is the name)

mxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`mxtunnel`, id of the Mist Tunnel

mxtunnel_name.description: when `interface`=`site_medge`, name of the mxtunnel that in mxtunnels under Site Setting

no_static_dns.description: whether to only allow client to use DNS that we’ve learned from DHCP response

no_static_ip.description: whether to only allow client that we’ve learned from DHCP exchange to talk

portal_allowed_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring)

portal_api_secret.description: api secret (auto-generated) that can be used to sign guest authorization requests

portal_denied_hostnames.description: list of hostnames without http(s):// (matched by substring), this takes precedence over portal_allowed_hostnames

portal_template_url.description: N.B portal_template will be forked out of wlan objects soon. To fetch portal_template, please query portal_template_url. To update portal_template, use Wlan Portal Template.

schedule.description: WLAN operating schedule, default is disabled

hours.description: time ranges, the key is mon / tue / wed / thu / fri / sat / sun, the value is time range in “HH:MM-HH:MM” (24-hour format), the minimum resolution is 30 minute

sle_excluded.description: whether to exclude this WLAN from SLE metrics

thumbnail.description: Url of portal background image thumbnail

use_eapol_v1.description: if `auth.type`==’eap’ or ‘psk’, should only be set for legacy client, such as pre-2004, 802.11b devices

vlan_pooling.description: vlan pooling allows AP to place client on different VLAN using a deterministic algorithm

wlan_limit_down_enabled.description: if downlink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wlan_limit_up_enabled.description: if uplink limiting for whole wlan is enabled

wxtunnel_id.description: when `interface`=`wxtunnel`, id of the WXLAN Tunnel

schema.description:
Webhook
NOTE: 
 * when `secret` is provided, two HTTP headers will be added:
   * `X-Mist-Signature-v2`: HMAC_SHA256(secret, body)
   * `X-Mist-Signature`: HMAC_SHA1(secret, body)
 * If `headers` format is invalid, “X-Mist-Error”: “headers format invalid” will be sent.
 * If total bytes of `headers` exceed 1000, “X-Mist-Error”: “headers too big” will be sent.
 * If any header value is not `string`, “X-Mist-Error”: “header[%s] not a string” will be sent.

headers.description: custom headers : the headers name and value must be string, total bytes of headers name and value must be less than 1000

secret.description: optional, when type=http-post, if provided, additional signature HTTP headers will be added (see note below)

topics.description: N.B. For org webhooks, only device-events/alarms/audits/client-join/client-sessions topics are supported.

verify_cert.description: when url uses HTTPS, whether to verify the certificate

default_role.description: default role to assign if there’s no match. By default, an assertion is treated as invalid when there’s no role matched

idp_cert.description: IDP Cert (used to verify the signed response)

ignore_unmatched_roles.description: ignore any unmatched roles provided in assertion. By default, an assertion is treated as invalid for any unmatched role

role_attr_extraction.description:

NameScheme
cn
  • The expected role attribute format in SAML Assertion is “CN=cn,OU=ou1,OU=ou2,…”
  • CN (the key) is case insensitive and exactly 1 CN is expected (or the entire entry will be ignored)
  • E.g. if role attribute is “CN=cn,OU=ou1,OU=ou2” then parsed role value is “cn”

alarmtemplate_id.description: Alarm Template ID, this takes precedence over the Org-level alarmtemplate_id

country_code.description: country code for the site (for AP config generation), in two-character

gatewaytemplate_id.description: Gateway Template ID, used by gateways

networktemplate_id.description: Network Template ID, this takes precedence over Site Settings

notes.description: optional, any notes about the site

rftemplate_id.description: RF Template ID, this takes precedence over Site Settings

device_updown_threshold.description: enable threshold-based device down delivery via 1) device-updowns webhooks topic, 2) Mist Alert Framework; e.g. send AP/SW/GW down event only if AP/SW/GW Up is not seen within the threshold in minutes; 0 - 30, default is 0 (trigger immediate)

disable_pcap.description: whether to disallow Mist to analyze pcap files (this is required for marvis pcap)

use_mxtunnel.description: whether to use Mist Tunnel for mgmt connectivity,  this takes precedence over use_wxtunnel

use_wxtunnel.description: whether to use wxtunnel for mgmt connectivity

freshness.description: days, required if password policy is enabled

max_pkt_len.description: max_len of non-management packets to capture

disable_local_ssh.description: whether to disable local SSH (by default, local SSH is enabled with allow_mist in Org is enabled

fips_zeroize_password.description: password required to zeroize devices (FIPS) on site level

limit_ssh_access.description: whether to allow certain SSH keys to SSH into the AP (see Site:Setting)

schema.description: Security Policy is designed to audit / catch discripancies between “what’s intended to be running” versus “what’s actually running” in a network. Many big organizations have separated Security and IT team (for good reasons). Each site can be assigned a security policy. Whenever an AP is provisioned, the configuration will be checked against the security policy. Any violations will be flagged in Device Config History where you can search for the when and where the violation occurs.

Many big organizations have separated Security and IT team (for good reasons). Each site can be assigned a security policy. Whenever an AP is provisioned, the configuration will be checked against the security policy. Any violations will be flagged in Device Config History where you can search for the when and where the violation occurs.

internet_access.description: whether this network has direct internet access

destination_nat.description: `property_name` may be an IP Address (i.e. "172.16.0.1"), and IP Address and Port (i.e. "172.16.0.1:8443") or a CIDR (i.e. "172.16.0.12/20")

restricted.description: by default, all access is allowed, to only allow certain traffic, make `restricted`=`true` and define service_policies

static_nat.description: `property_name` may be an IP Address (i.e. "172.16.0.1"), and IP Address and Port (i.e. "172.16.0.1:8443") or a CIDR (i.e. "172.16.0.12/20")

isolation.description: whether to allow clients in the network to talk to each other

destination_nat.description: if `routed` = `false` (usually at Spoke), but some hosts needs to be reachable from Hub

nat_pool.description: if `routed` = `false` (usually at Spoke), but some hosts needs to be reachable from Hub

static_nat.description: if `routed` = `false` (usually at Spoke), but some hosts needs to be reachable from Hub

vpn_access.description: whether this network can be accessed from vpn
